in the game.

242
00:11:11,821 --> 00:11:14,042
Many games, and also the old ones,

243
00:11:14,082 --> 00:11:15,923
the Desperados and Commandos, did something

244
00:11:15,963 --> 00:11:17,484
where they had infinite ammo,

245
00:11:17,524 --> 00:11:19,425
and you could basically start shooting at any time,

246
00:11:19,725 --> 00:11:21,606
and just draw all the guards on the map to your,

247
00:11:21,786 --> 00:11:22,087
and just...

248
00:11:22,682 --> 00:11:26,764
kill them. And we didn't like that and we also realized that we would never be able

249
00:11:26,804 --> 00:11:31,567
to create good gun gameplay mechanics and good stealth mechanics at the same time. So

250
00:11:31,647 --> 00:11:36,709
what we decided was that we will just not do shooting and shootouts in a big way so

251
00:11:36,769 --> 00:11:42,212
our guns are more like stealth guns. They have a very small range of audio or noise

252
00:11:42,452 --> 00:11:46,034
so people don't hear them as much but you have a very limited amount of ammunition.

253
00:11:46,434 --> 00:11:49,716
And the role is basically that if you're stuck in some sort of setup and you don't know what

254
00:11:49,756 --> 00:11:50,356
to do and you just

255
00:11:50,537 --> 00:11:52,598
You can't figure it out, you just use your guns,

256
00:11:52,699 --> 00:11:54,020
shoot everyone in that one setup,

257
00:11:54,060 --> 00:11:54,921
and then you can move along.

258
00:11:55,181 --> 00:11:57,543
So it's basically a joker or a small cheat that you have.

259
00:11:59,416 --> 00:12:00,877
And they all have a health pack, but whatever.

260
00:12:01,237 --> 00:12:05,099
So the important part about this was that we made a system

261
00:12:05,119 --> 00:12:07,601
where every character has each type of skill.

262
00:12:08,341 --> 00:12:11,243
And the one that is most driver-like, I guess,

263
00:12:11,343 --> 00:12:13,444
would be Takuma because he can't carry bodies,

264
00:12:13,504 --> 00:12:15,305
he cannot climb, he cannot kill anyone,

265
00:12:15,606 --> 00:12:17,627
but he's extremely powerful aside from that.

266
00:12:18,267 --> 00:12:19,708
All of his skills are very strong.

267
00:12:19,748 --> 00:12:21,689
The tanuki is the strongest distraction in the game.

268
00:12:22,089 --> 00:12:24,271
The grenade, the normal one is not as good,

269
00:12:24,371 --> 00:12:25,792
but you can switch it to a stun grenade,

270
00:12:25,812 --> 00:12:27,032
which is completely overpowered.

271
00:12:28,873 --> 00:12:30,534
Yeah, the snipe is just strong.

272
00:12:31,674 --> 00:12:32,974
Alright, so that's enough for characters.

273
00:12:33,174 --> 00:12:36,495
I'm going to do sort of a deep dive into one game design topic

274
00:12:36,515 --> 00:12:38,176
between each of these broader topics.

275
00:12:38,476 --> 00:12:40,416
It's supposed to be a warp vortex,

276
00:12:40,456 --> 00:12:41,577
but it looks more like a snake.

277
00:12:42,217 --> 00:12:43,257
A snail, I'm sorry.

278
00:12:44,057 --> 00:12:45,918
Alright, for this one I'm going to talk about shadow mode,

279
00:12:46,118 --> 00:12:47,618
which is a prominent feature in the game.

280
00:12:48,795 --> 00:12:51,978
Something that's very important to us is that you're playing a team, right?

281
00:12:51,998 --> 00:12:53,199
This was one of the pillars we had.

282
00:12:53,259 --> 00:12:55,401
You shouldn't feel like there's individuals running around.

283
00:12:55,461 --> 00:12:57,643
It should be like a team that is working together,

284
00:12:57,703 --> 00:13:01,786
because this sort of is different from any stealth games where you're just by yourself usually.

285
00:13:02,227 --> 00:13:05,109
And so what we thought of in the beginning is that we make team actions,

286
00:13:05,249 --> 00:13:09,052
which would be like two characters working together and creating this new skill.

287
00:13:09,192 --> 00:13:10,894
And this would be true for every character.

288
00:13:10,974 --> 00:13:13,276
Every character combination would have their own team action.

289
00:13:14,123 --> 00:13:16,046
Desperados did that in one of their sequels.

290
00:13:16,227 --> 00:13:18,531
It did not work out for them, and I know why now,

291
00:13:18,611 --> 00:13:19,593
because we tried it as well.

292
00:13:21,256 --> 00:13:25,344
The problem with this is that team actions.

293
00:13:26,737 --> 00:13:28,337
add a lot of complexity to the game.

294
00:13:29,097 --> 00:13:30,458
It's hard enough already, I mean,

295
00:13:30,518 --> 00:13:32,618
every character has two skills you have to learn, right?

296
00:13:32,658 --> 00:13:33,879
The distraction and the special.

297
00:13:34,139 --> 00:13:35,659
And that is hard enough for people already.

298
00:13:35,999 --> 00:13:38,320
It would take them a long time to really get the hang

299
00:13:38,360 --> 00:13:39,360
of how to use a character.

300
00:13:39,641 --> 00:13:42,401
Now imagine if we add five to 10 skills on top of that

301
00:13:42,441 --> 00:13:43,842
that are just very situational,

302
00:13:43,882 --> 00:13:45,142
you can't even use them all the time.

303
00:13:45,422 --> 00:13:48,344
and you have to try to learn those and really use them,

304
00:13:48,484 --> 00:13:49,725
that was not gonna work.

305
00:13:50,746 --> 00:13:53,228
And the second one was that we had a couple of good examples

306
00:13:53,268 --> 00:13:53,949
for team action.

307
00:13:53,969 --> 00:13:57,172
For example, we had the idea that Aiko could use Mugen

308
00:13:57,212 --> 00:13:59,053
sort of as act like he's her husband

309
00:13:59,093 --> 00:14:01,215
and sort of shuttle him through enemy vision

310
00:14:01,275 --> 00:14:02,796
because they wouldn't think he's suspicious

311
00:14:03,237 --> 00:14:05,619
or Mugen could bunk up other characters

312
00:14:05,679 --> 00:14:06,900
and help them climb like a ladder.

313
00:14:07,901 --> 00:14:10,703
But it sort of stopped after that

314
00:14:10,923 --> 00:14:12,284
and we would have needed 10 or more.

315
00:14:12,465 --> 00:14:14,066
So yeah, we scrapped that.

316
00:14:14,924 --> 00:14:16,284
And we did the planning mode thing.

317
00:14:16,444 --> 00:14:17,885
That also existed in Desperados.

318
00:14:17,905 --> 00:14:18,865
It was a little hard to use

319
00:14:19,065 --> 00:14:20,766
because the controls were not as tight,

320
00:14:21,886 --> 00:14:23,206
and they are for us as well.

321
00:14:23,846 --> 00:14:25,467
But the idea behind the planning mode,

322
00:14:25,487 --> 00:14:27,707
if you don't know it, is that you can plan one action

323
00:14:27,767 --> 00:14:28,808
for each character you have,

324
00:14:29,608 --> 00:14:31,508
and then have them executed at a later time,

325
00:14:31,708 --> 00:14:33,169
together or separate.

326
00:14:35,952 --> 00:14:37,833
This is very important for gamepad controls.

327
00:14:38,113 --> 00:14:39,413
We knew from the beginning that we're gonna do

328
00:14:39,433 --> 00:14:41,514
a console version, so we worked on gamepad controls

329
00:14:41,654 --> 00:14:42,215
from the beginning.

330
00:14:43,095 --> 00:14:45,156
And it is very different because you control

331
00:14:45,176 --> 00:14:46,997
the character directly, right?

332
00:14:47,037 --> 00:14:48,738
It's very immersive in that case.

333
00:14:49,498 --> 00:14:53,380
So on a computer you could simply just send

334
00:14:53,440 --> 00:14:55,681
a character somewhere and do something else

335
00:14:55,701 --> 00:14:58,182
with another character, but on a gamepad you can't

336
00:14:58,482 --> 00:15:00,063
because you have to control the character yourself.

337
00:15:00,403 --> 00:15:01,904
So shadow mode becomes very important

338
00:15:02,064 --> 00:15:03,045
if you're playing with a gamepad.

339
00:15:04,245 --> 00:15:04,345
And...

340
00:15:04,667 --> 00:15:07,649
And what it turned out to be is sort of a do-it-yourself team action.

341
00:15:07,829 --> 00:15:10,831
And it was brilliant because we didn't have to teach you any new skills.

342
00:15:10,871 --> 00:15:14,594
You could basically use the skills that you already knew, combine them, make the game

343
00:15:14,654 --> 00:15:18,217
feel like a team game, and voila, everything worked out well.

344
00:15:18,778 --> 00:15:22,020
And I think this is also some of the most powerful moments in the game are when you

345
00:15:22,120 --> 00:15:23,661
pull off a successful shadow mode.

346
00:15:23,701 --> 00:15:25,203
So that worked out well.

347
00:15:26,023 --> 00:15:31,087
And something that often comes up is the question why we only have one action that you can save.

348
00:15:31,147 --> 00:15:32,488
And why not infinite actions?

349
00:15:32,528 --> 00:15:33,489
It would be so much cooler.

350
00:15:34,740 --> 00:15:38,541
We actually had that during development and it had a couple of problems.

351
00:15:39,762 --> 00:15:41,423
It was pretty awesome, I have to admit it.

352
00:15:41,483 --> 00:15:44,524
Like if you saw people just doing these insane things

353
00:15:44,584 --> 00:15:47,025
where they would make insane queues and chains of

354
00:15:47,085 --> 00:15:49,446
I throw a shuriken there, I walk over there, I use my stone,

355
00:15:49,466 --> 00:15:51,587
the shuriken, I pick it up again, the cooldown,

356
00:15:51,667 --> 00:15:54,708
and they would do insane things and basically clear parts of the whole map

357
00:15:54,749 --> 00:15:55,549
just in shadow mode.

358
00:15:56,369 --> 00:16:00,011
And that was fun, but that's not how we want you to play our game.

359
00:16:00,411 --> 00:16:03,052
In our game a very important aspect is the real-time aspect.

360
00:16:03,347 --> 00:16:04,768
And it's the aspect of execution.

361
00:16:05,068 --> 00:16:07,148
You cannot just plan like in a turn-based game,

362
00:16:07,168 --> 00:16:08,449
but you have to execute as well.

363
00:16:08,889 --> 00:16:10,209
And if Shadow Mode is that powerful,

364
00:16:10,229 --> 00:16:11,530
you don't have to execute anymore.

365
00:16:11,570 --> 00:16:14,411
You just plan it and you look and see what happens.

366
00:16:15,331 --> 00:16:17,292
And the other one was that the more complexity

367
00:16:17,332 --> 00:16:20,313
the feature had, the more tools players wanted

368
00:16:20,353 --> 00:16:20,933
to work with it.

369
00:16:20,993 --> 00:16:23,734
So they wanted timelines where they could rearrange

370
00:16:23,754 --> 00:16:25,014
the actions they had set,

371
00:16:25,094 --> 00:16:27,195
or they wanted a pause function where they say,

372
00:16:27,455 --> 00:16:29,436
you walk there and then you wait three seconds

373
00:16:29,476 --> 00:16:30,396
and then you do this action.

374
00:16:31,326 --> 00:16:34,150
And that would have been a nightmare from all sort of standpoints.

375
00:16:34,691 --> 00:16:35,933
So we didn't do it.

376
00:16:37,035 --> 00:16:39,378
And the lesson we learned is that less is more.

377
00:16:39,719 --> 00:16:40,761
Wow, big lesson.

378
00:16:41,562 --> 00:16:42,884
I guess nobody heard that before.

379
00:16:43,565 --> 00:16:43,705
But.

380
00:16:44,782 --> 00:16:46,904
The big part that was new for us was the fact

381
00:16:46,964 --> 00:16:48,686
that what we actually had was fun, right?

382
00:16:48,726 --> 00:16:50,067
It was not something where you just have

383
00:16:50,407 --> 00:16:53,350
this huge pile of features, but a lot of stuff is added on

384
00:16:53,390 --> 00:16:54,992
and somebody's coming, yeah, you should do less,

385
00:16:55,032 --> 00:16:55,673
that would be better.

386
00:16:56,013 --> 00:16:57,675
It was fun, it was a very good thing,

387
00:16:57,695 --> 00:16:59,957
and there's games who have this planning mode thing

388
00:16:59,997 --> 00:17:02,039
as their main mechanic, but it just wasn't our game,

389
00:17:02,159 --> 00:17:04,642
so we had to cut it out, and the game's better for it.

390
00:17:06,603 --> 00:17:08,025
Let's talk about level design.

391
00:17:10,057 --> 00:17:11,098
I could talk a lot about that.

392
00:17:11,158 --> 00:17:12,620
It's going to be rather short, though,

393
00:17:12,840 --> 00:17:15,623
because there's a lot going on in this talk.

394
00:17:16,644 --> 00:17:18,126
This is the mission eight of the game.

395
00:17:18,666 --> 00:17:20,428
And as you can see, the map is very big.

396
00:17:20,668 --> 00:17:21,469
You are this big.

397
00:17:21,489 --> 00:17:23,832
If you can't see it, this is you.

398
00:17:25,967 --> 00:17:29,910
So what is very important if you have a mission where people spend one to four hours on,

399
00:17:30,591 --> 00:17:31,831
is that the mission is cool.

400
00:17:32,432 --> 00:17:35,474
As soon as the mission is bad or boring, they're probably going to stop playing your game

401
00:17:35,514 --> 00:17:37,996
because they know they have to spend a couple of hours on that mission.

402
00:17:38,916 --> 00:17:40,538
And they also have to be very unique.

403
00:17:40,638 --> 00:17:43,199
And this is sort of the first big thing that we wanted to do.

404
00:17:43,219 --> 00:17:45,881
And this is something that Commandos 2 does the best, I guess.

405
00:17:45,921 --> 00:17:47,883
They have very unique settings and great maps.

406
00:17:48,463 --> 00:17:49,604
So we took that inspiration.

407
00:17:50,735 --> 00:17:53,877
And the idea is basically that if you and a friend have played the game,

408
00:17:53,897 --> 00:17:56,558
this is sort of a test you can make to see if your maps are unique,

409
00:17:57,579 --> 00:18:00,500
if you can describe to them a mission with one or two words

410
00:18:00,860 --> 00:18:03,161
and they know which one you're talking about instantly,

411
00:18:03,521 --> 00:18:05,222
then it's probably unique enough.

412
00:18:06,343 --> 00:18:10,345
And the important thing about this is that we did also not want you to...

413
00:18:11,074 --> 00:18:14,357
get into a new map and realized it's the same thing again.

414
00:18:14,817 --> 00:18:17,059
And you know you have to play that for two hours now.

415
00:18:17,419 --> 00:18:19,380
So that was very important that things look differently.

416
00:18:19,661 --> 00:18:21,202
I'm gonna talk about that a little bit more later

417
00:18:21,222 --> 00:18:22,142
when I talk about pacing.

418
00:18:24,464 --> 00:18:26,446
Another big thing was the emotional state

419
00:18:26,486 --> 00:18:28,187
that you want you to be in if you play a mission.

420
00:18:28,427 --> 00:18:30,729
This is very high level, but it's important to know that

421
00:18:30,989 --> 00:18:32,810
like if you wanna be consistent.

422
00:18:33,979 --> 00:18:39,322
So if you open up the mission, you're very very happy. Everything is new. It's looking gorgeous. You're scrolling over the whole map

423
00:18:39,342 --> 00:18:42,664
You're like, oh wow, this is beautiful. Look at that landmark. Look at this nice building

424
00:18:43,004 --> 00:18:48,446
Look at this and then it sort of dawns to you that you have to actually play all of this and you see things

425
00:18:48,486 --> 00:18:53,589
Like oh my god, there's some Samurai over there. There's a huge patrol of guys. How am I ever going to?

426
00:18:54,557 --> 00:18:56,057
and you want to quit, but then you're like,

427
00:18:56,137 --> 00:18:57,077
okay, no, I can do this.

428
00:18:57,778 --> 00:19:00,358
I've had certain missions before, I can do this one as well,

429
00:19:00,558 --> 00:19:02,839
and then you enter in the emotional core loop of our game,

430
00:19:02,859 --> 00:19:05,820
which is basically utter despair into happiness,

431
00:19:06,020 --> 00:19:08,461
into I can do this, and many quick saves,

432
00:19:08,561 --> 00:19:10,321
and maybe rage quits in between.

433
00:19:11,462 --> 00:19:14,142
And in the end, you feel like a god.

434
00:19:14,502 --> 00:19:16,183
You're in a purple cloud of puffiness,

435
00:19:16,383 --> 00:19:18,924
and you're very happy, and the big thing is

436
00:19:18,944 --> 00:19:20,564
that you can scroll over the whole map

437
00:19:20,604 --> 00:19:21,885
that you have actually just completed,

438
00:19:21,945 --> 00:19:23,225
and see everything that you've done.

439
00:19:24,697 --> 00:19:26,378
This is important, and this is very, very good.

440
00:19:27,259 --> 00:19:27,900
And we want that.

441
00:19:28,520 --> 00:19:30,282
We could have done more in that department, I think.

442
00:19:30,322 --> 00:19:32,003
We could have added to the stats screen

443
00:19:32,023 --> 00:19:33,185
some sort of replay function

444
00:19:33,205 --> 00:19:34,926
where you can just see what actually happened,

445
00:19:34,946 --> 00:19:36,388
and you did this there, and you did that.

446
00:19:36,448 --> 00:19:38,690
That's something we're probably gonna do for our next game.

447
00:19:40,531 --> 00:19:42,673
Yeah, but this is very, very important,

448
00:19:43,014 --> 00:19:45,957
and giving you that feeling of satisfaction in the end.

449
00:19:47,078 --> 00:19:48,619
So basically, every mission is the same

450
00:19:48,759 --> 00:19:50,521
as doing a small setup, right?

451
00:19:51,896 --> 00:19:53,656
And I want to talk about openness a little bit.

452
00:19:54,137 --> 00:19:55,577
One of our key pillars in the game,

453
00:19:55,597 --> 00:19:57,717
the level design, was that you should

454
00:19:58,018 --> 00:19:59,138
be able to play it your way.

455
00:19:59,458 --> 00:20:01,719
Everybody should have the chance to play different

456
00:20:01,899 --> 00:20:04,039
things, and every puzzle had to play different

457
00:20:04,059 --> 00:20:05,640
approaches. And this doesn't only

458
00:20:05,700 --> 00:20:07,860
apply to the small enemy setups, but also

459
00:20:07,900 --> 00:20:10,061
to the whole map. This is Mission 5.

460
00:20:10,161 --> 00:20:11,401
It's the first mission that we built.

461
00:20:11,421 --> 00:20:12,921
It was sort of a vertical slice.

462
00:20:14,102 --> 00:20:15,602
And I think it's one of the best, which is

463
00:20:15,862 --> 00:20:17,843
awkward, because we didn't learn much,

464
00:20:17,963 --> 00:20:18,223
I guess.

465
00:20:20,243 --> 00:20:20,383
But...

466
00:20:21,622 --> 00:20:25,266
In the beginning it's very linear, you get up to this gate and then the mission basically opens up.

467
00:20:25,366 --> 00:20:26,847
And you can go left or you can go right.

468
00:20:26,907 --> 00:20:29,270
And the briefing tells you this, right? It tells you there's two paths.

469
00:20:29,850 --> 00:20:32,513
And something that's very important if you're designing for openness

470
00:20:32,633 --> 00:20:34,555
is that you actually show players the paths.

471
00:20:35,736 --> 00:20:38,719
If you have 20 paths but they're all obfuscated and you're like,

472
00:20:38,759 --> 00:20:40,701
yeah, the player has to be clever and find them,

473
00:20:40,781 --> 00:20:42,983
then they won't look and they won't find them

474
00:20:43,083 --> 00:20:46,326
and they won't realize that this is an open game and they will think it's linear.

475
00:20:46,627 --> 00:20:48,788
So what we always try to do is something like this T-shape,

476
00:20:48,808 --> 00:20:50,409
where we say, OK, you can go left, you can go right.

477
00:20:51,210 --> 00:20:53,832
And also be aware of the fact that you are not

478
00:20:53,932 --> 00:20:56,253
losing content if they are not playing the other part.

479
00:20:56,894 --> 00:20:59,135
The choice is only meaningful because they

480
00:20:59,175 --> 00:21:00,516
don't get to play the part, right?

481
00:21:00,757 --> 00:21:02,578
If they would end up in the same thing anyway,

482
00:21:02,598 --> 00:21:03,779
there wouldn't be a choice, and the game

483
00:21:03,819 --> 00:21:05,380
wouldn't feel open or good at all.

484
00:21:05,920 --> 00:21:07,761
Plus, you can always have replayability.

485
00:21:07,801 --> 00:21:09,703
If the player chooses to play this mission again,

486
00:21:09,723 --> 00:21:10,964
they will choose the other path and have

487
00:21:10,984 --> 00:21:12,184
a completely different experience.

488
00:21:13,183 --> 00:21:15,345
And there also are obfuscated paths in this mission.

489
00:21:15,865 --> 00:21:18,227
You can just go straight ahead and climb up the building,

490
00:21:18,267 --> 00:21:19,728
but most people don't find that.

491
00:21:20,209 --> 00:21:23,251
But it's cool, because if you replay it, you might find that.

492
00:21:23,271 --> 00:21:24,052
You might feel clever.

493
00:21:24,072 --> 00:21:25,633
We don't tell it to you in a briefing,

494
00:21:25,673 --> 00:21:27,735
and we do that sort of stuff a lot.

495
00:21:29,655 --> 00:21:32,677
I want to talk about bottlenecks, because if everything was very open and you didn't

496
00:21:32,697 --> 00:21:36,320
have any bottlenecks, then the game would be very boring, especially ours, because people

497
00:21:36,340 --> 00:21:39,102
could just sneak through everything and leave everything behind.

498
00:21:39,943 --> 00:21:44,467
So how do we do bottlenecks and how do we make them still fun and not feel frustrating?

499
00:21:44,987 --> 00:21:48,770
So the first thing that we do is basically bottlenecks always revolve around Takuma or

500
00:21:48,810 --> 00:21:52,873
Mugen who cannot climb or swim, so you always have to drag them through, sort of.

501
00:21:54,752 --> 00:21:56,733
In this case, this is the bottleneck.

502
00:21:56,773 --> 00:21:59,014
You have to get Takuma to this sniper tower on the left,

503
00:21:59,074 --> 00:22:01,095
but he cannot swim, so he has to go over that thing.

504
00:22:01,955 --> 00:22:04,856
And what's important here is that while it is a bottleneck

505
00:22:04,876 --> 00:22:07,617
to get Takuma there, you have infinite possibilities

506
00:22:07,657 --> 00:22:09,598
with your other characters on how to solve that thing.

507
00:22:09,618 --> 00:22:11,319
You can swim around the whole island,

508
00:22:11,359 --> 00:22:12,879
you can get out anywhere you want to,

509
00:22:13,399 --> 00:22:15,560
and approach the setup in a very, very open way,

510
00:22:15,580 --> 00:22:16,961
and there are multiple solutions to it.

511
00:22:17,241 --> 00:22:19,362
So it doesn't really feel like a bad bottleneck

512
00:22:19,382 --> 00:22:20,762
where you're like, I have to do this now.

513
00:22:21,363 --> 00:22:23,083
It still feels open, and you can be creative.

514
00:22:24,183 --> 00:22:27,065
So, yeah, that's enough for level design.

515
00:22:27,185 --> 00:22:29,887
Let's do another deep dive thingy.

516
00:22:30,588 --> 00:22:33,150
Something that we learned, which is also pretty obvious, I guess,

517
00:22:33,170 --> 00:22:36,292
for many people, but it's about how people approach

518
00:22:36,392 --> 00:22:37,693
problem solving in your game.

519
00:22:37,954 --> 00:22:41,436
So we have a player, and the player faces a problem.

520
00:22:41,556 --> 00:22:43,358
In our case, usually a setup of some guards.

521
00:22:44,482 --> 00:22:48,803
And there is this assumption players have on how they are approaching a problem in our game,

522
00:22:48,843 --> 00:22:51,423
because it's called Shadow Tactics, it's a tactical game, right?

523
00:22:51,683 --> 00:22:55,664
You have strategy, you're in this view, in this RTS view where you can see everything.

524
00:22:55,704 --> 00:22:58,985
So people think that they're actually approaching problems very holistically,

525
00:22:59,045 --> 00:23:02,626
and checking everything out, and then narrowing it down, and then starting to work,

526
00:23:02,666 --> 00:23:03,966
but that is not what they're doing.

527
00:23:04,407 --> 00:23:09,268
In reality, they do this. They see a guard, and this is the circle, sort of the tactical horizon,

528
00:23:09,888 --> 00:23:11,388
things they actually see.

529
00:23:12,068 --> 00:23:13,389
And they just go in and kill the guard,

530
00:23:13,469 --> 00:23:14,869
and then they get seen and they quick load.

531
00:23:16,270 --> 00:23:17,710
And they see, okay, this guy is in there,

532
00:23:17,750 --> 00:23:19,850
so they add that guy to their horizon, sort of.

533
00:23:19,910 --> 00:23:21,571
And they keep doing that over and over

534
00:23:21,631 --> 00:23:23,711
until they have actually understood how the setup works.

535
00:23:25,052 --> 00:23:26,652
And it is very important to understand that,

536
00:23:26,672 --> 00:23:27,752
because they might tell you

537
00:23:27,812 --> 00:23:29,973
that they are playing very strategically,

538
00:23:30,033 --> 00:23:31,093
but they are usually not.

539
00:23:31,173 --> 00:23:33,414
I'm sure that many people are, but many weren't.

540
00:23:34,474 --> 00:23:36,175
And what this meant for our level design was,

541
00:23:36,579 --> 00:23:39,080
that we had to make sure that things are not too far away

542
00:23:39,140 --> 00:23:41,201
from the center of attention that you're actually playing in.

543
00:23:41,961 --> 00:23:43,882
For example, we don't have large patrols

544
00:23:43,922 --> 00:23:45,883
that are going like many minutes around the map

545
00:23:46,303 --> 00:23:47,844
because that would just be bad.

546
00:23:47,864 --> 00:23:49,805
You would play the game and then suddenly they would come in

547
00:23:49,865 --> 00:23:51,485
and screw everything up for you.

548
00:23:52,326 --> 00:23:54,867
And we try to have guards close to each other.

549
00:23:55,047 --> 00:23:58,688
And this doesn't work all the time, but we tried doing that.

550
00:24:02,413 --> 00:24:06,815
Another thing we did here was that we cleared off the areas very clear.

551
00:24:06,975 --> 00:24:10,275
So you cannot see from one area into the other.

552
00:24:10,315 --> 00:24:12,976
You can always rely on the fact that if you are in one area,

553
00:24:13,076 --> 00:24:17,517
guards from another area will not disturb you, at least most of the time.

554
00:24:18,157 --> 00:24:20,998
So the lesson we learned here is that what people tell you

555
00:24:21,078 --> 00:24:23,378
about how they approach problems in the game is not really true.

556
00:24:24,059 --> 00:24:26,699
And we thought about why this is the case in our game,

557
00:24:26,739 --> 00:24:28,980
and it's very clear we could have seen that from the beginning

558
00:24:29,020 --> 00:24:30,940
because shadow tactics is very iterative, right?

559
00:24:31,964 --> 00:24:33,844
We teach you to quick save all the time,

560
00:24:33,904 --> 00:24:35,985
so there's basically no punishment for failure.

561
00:24:36,045 --> 00:24:37,486
The game screams that at you.

562
00:24:37,526 --> 00:24:38,706
It's like, just try things out.

563
00:24:39,166 --> 00:24:41,067
The quick load time is very low, just keep going.

564
00:24:41,747 --> 00:24:44,429
And of course they don't think holistically

565
00:24:44,489 --> 00:24:46,849
and watch everything because they don't have to, right?

566
00:24:46,870 --> 00:24:47,930
And it's in our core mechanics,

567
00:24:47,970 --> 00:24:49,090
and we could have seen that earlier.

568
00:24:51,171 --> 00:24:51,591
Story.

569
00:24:51,611 --> 00:24:53,992
I'm gonna drink something real quick.

570
00:24:54,913 --> 00:24:56,533
So, the most important rule.

571
00:24:59,159 --> 00:25:01,560
we had for our story was that the plot is not important,

572
00:25:01,800 --> 00:25:02,901
but the characters are important.

573
00:25:04,001 --> 00:25:06,743
And the plot had to work with many, many restrictions

574
00:25:07,143 --> 00:25:08,984
from a game design and level design standpoint.

575
00:25:09,024 --> 00:25:10,305
I'm gonna talk about that in a bit.

576
00:25:10,645 --> 00:25:12,145
So it's structured very simple

577
00:25:12,366 --> 00:25:14,947
and it had to facilitate certain things.

578
00:25:15,567 --> 00:25:17,808
It's basically the Shogun is fighting Kagesama,

579
00:25:17,848 --> 00:25:19,809
who's this ominous bad guy.

580
00:25:20,009 --> 00:25:20,750
You don't know who he is.

581
00:25:21,790 --> 00:25:23,491
And the important part here is that

582
00:25:24,519 --> 00:25:28,964
The Shogun can send you anywhere because we have these missions where you're on a mountaintop,

583
00:25:29,004 --> 00:25:34,129
it's winter, oh, you're at a lake, it's summer, and it's impossible to tell a story that feels

584
00:25:34,149 --> 00:25:36,952
like a journey very much if you have a structure like that.

585
00:25:37,133 --> 00:25:40,016
That's what I talked about with the different settings before, that we want every map to

586
00:25:40,056 --> 00:25:40,877
feel fresh and new.

587
00:25:41,257 --> 00:25:42,899
This is a big hit for the story, right?

588
00:25:43,239 --> 00:25:44,541
You cannot do certain things then.

589
00:25:45,401 --> 00:25:47,023
And that's why we...

590
00:25:48,117 --> 00:25:50,099
And also the characters that you have in a mission

591
00:25:50,199 --> 00:25:51,440
are not defined by the story.

592
00:25:51,480 --> 00:25:53,122
They are very much defined by the pacing,

593
00:25:53,542 --> 00:25:55,144
so the writer can't just say,

594
00:25:55,184 --> 00:25:56,745
yeah, I want this character to be here

595
00:25:56,826 --> 00:25:58,127
because he will not be there.

596
00:25:59,668 --> 00:26:02,011
So we did this mostly in cut scenes, the plot thing.

597
00:26:02,591 --> 00:26:05,034
Between the missions you get a cut scene and that's that.

598
00:26:06,195 --> 00:26:09,378
But the more important part of storytelling that we had

599
00:26:09,719 --> 00:26:11,781
is about our characters and how we talk about them.

600
00:26:12,433 --> 00:26:15,535
The first thing we do is we have something like we call context dialogues,

601
00:26:15,655 --> 00:26:19,317
sort of a dialogue that either triggers if you walk into a volume with the player character,

602
00:26:19,677 --> 00:26:23,340
or if you do an action, you kill a guard, whatever, then these banter things trigger.

603
00:26:23,940 --> 00:26:28,142
And they are very weird because we're in Edo, Japan, this is very early,

604
00:26:28,342 --> 00:26:31,604
and they sort of have Skype, they can just talk to each other over the whole map.

605
00:26:32,304 --> 00:26:34,866
And some people are offended by that and they don't like it, but...

606
00:26:35,620 --> 00:26:38,342
Realize that people want your characters to talk to each other,

607
00:26:38,562 --> 00:26:40,884
so they will have a lot higher suspension of disbelief

608
00:26:41,124 --> 00:26:43,726
if something like this happens, if you do it right.

609
00:26:43,966 --> 00:26:46,408
And we had certain things that we had to change

610
00:26:47,328 --> 00:26:51,632
and had to work into the game that would make this less awkward.

611
00:26:51,672 --> 00:26:54,033
For example, when a character walks into a trigger volume

612
00:26:54,094 --> 00:26:55,575
and one of these dialogues triggers,

613
00:26:56,582 --> 00:26:58,883
it's always that correct character that starts talking.

614
00:26:58,983 --> 00:27:00,344
So every dialogue is written in a way

615
00:27:00,384 --> 00:27:02,205
that there's a beginning line for each character

616
00:27:02,225 --> 00:27:04,307
in the mission, and then the dialogue will go on.

617
00:27:04,707 --> 00:27:05,948
And this way it feels less awkward

618
00:27:05,968 --> 00:27:08,009
because sort of you are initiating the dialogue

619
00:27:08,029 --> 00:27:10,391
and it's not someone screaming at you from 400 meters away.

620
00:27:11,892 --> 00:27:13,613
And this worked out really well, I think,

621
00:27:13,653 --> 00:27:15,715
and we got a lot of character things across

622
00:27:15,775 --> 00:27:18,136
with that and the personalities.

623
00:27:19,017 --> 00:27:19,677
And the other one is...

624
00:27:21,837 --> 00:27:22,838
We call them player barks.

625
00:27:23,378 --> 00:27:25,299
Barks are many things, so you might not

626
00:27:25,339 --> 00:27:26,459
call them that in your studio.

627
00:27:26,499 --> 00:27:29,200
But it's when you select the character, what they say

628
00:27:29,240 --> 00:27:30,601
when you use a shuriken or whatever.

629
00:27:30,921 --> 00:27:34,022
This work, work, yes, my lord stuff from Warcraft 3

630
00:27:34,382 --> 00:27:35,463
would be an example of that.

631
00:27:35,923 --> 00:27:38,404
And we try to use that for storytelling in something

632
00:27:38,724 --> 00:27:40,625
I haven't seen as much, and I wonder why,

633
00:27:40,685 --> 00:27:42,706
because it's the best way to do it.

634
00:27:43,946 --> 00:27:46,287
Something very bad happens at some point in your story.

635
00:27:47,640 --> 00:27:49,540
After that, for two missions, we sort of completely

636
00:27:49,600 --> 00:27:51,541
swapped the dialogue lines your characters say

637
00:27:52,221 --> 00:27:54,822
if you use them and make them walk around or use skills,

638
00:27:55,242 --> 00:27:56,382
because they are depressed.

639
00:27:56,662 --> 00:28:00,543
Because it would be very awkward if you have depressed dialogue

640
00:28:00,563 --> 00:28:02,144
where he's like, oh my god, I'm so sad.

641
00:28:02,524 --> 00:28:03,304
This is so bad.

642
00:28:03,324 --> 00:28:04,024
And then you select them.

643
00:28:04,044 --> 00:28:05,605
He's like, yes, sir, I'm going to do that.

644
00:28:06,305 --> 00:28:07,285
It doesn't feel right.

645
00:28:08,085 --> 00:28:10,486
And I think we could have done a lot more with that, used that.

646
00:28:11,527 --> 00:28:12,948
changing this stuff up a little more.

647
00:28:13,128 --> 00:28:14,248
Well, we did it a little bit with,

648
00:28:14,689 --> 00:28:16,810
there's a snow map, they might say things like,

649
00:28:16,850 --> 00:28:19,512
there's snow in my armor, but I think

650
00:28:19,632 --> 00:28:22,353
from an emotional standpoint, this is a very underused tool

651
00:28:22,614 --> 00:28:25,395
in RTS-like games that you can do very much with.

652
00:28:28,437 --> 00:28:28,978
Pacing.

653
00:28:30,018 --> 00:28:31,579
I'm realizing I'm talking very fast,

654
00:28:31,699 --> 00:28:33,641
so I might slow down a bit.

655
00:28:34,481 --> 00:28:36,703
I don't see much about pacing,

656
00:28:36,743 --> 00:28:38,464
so this might be very, very basic,

657
00:28:38,584 --> 00:28:40,305
and you might get bored now, but,

658
00:28:41,713 --> 00:28:44,894
It's an important thing to me and also for our game,

659
00:28:44,914 --> 00:28:45,934
so I wanted to talk about it.

660
00:28:45,974 --> 00:28:48,535
And if anybody of you is into that stuff,

661
00:28:48,575 --> 00:28:50,196
like pacing of the whole game, talk to me,

662
00:28:50,216 --> 00:28:51,916
I wanna learn, I want new things.

663
00:28:52,936 --> 00:28:55,417
So Shadow Tactics is about 25 hours long.

664
00:28:56,598 --> 00:28:59,659
And the biggest fear I had all the time

665
00:28:59,719 --> 00:29:01,619
was that people would get bored halfway through,

666
00:29:01,699 --> 00:29:03,920
because there is not very much in the game, actually.

667
00:29:04,400 --> 00:29:05,881
We have three enemy types, right?

668
00:29:07,053 --> 00:29:09,457
They are basically all the same, they just react differently.

669
00:29:09,537 --> 00:29:12,823
But they don't have different weapons or huge different behaviors.

670
00:29:12,883 --> 00:29:15,608
In the beginning, we had concepts of guards like that would maybe.

671
00:29:16,219 --> 00:29:19,221
gun around with torches and sort of burn the bushes you're hiding in,

672
00:29:19,261 --> 00:29:22,383
and ninja characters that hide in bushes, and we cut all of that,

673
00:29:22,443 --> 00:29:23,663
nothing of that made it into the game.

674
00:29:23,984 --> 00:29:26,225
So it's very simple, and we only have three guard types,

675
00:29:26,325 --> 00:29:29,907
so it's not much variety coming from that, right?

676
00:29:30,187 --> 00:29:33,489
Then we have five characters, but we introduced them in the first third of the game,

677
00:29:33,909 --> 00:29:35,370
and they do not change at all.

678
00:29:35,510 --> 00:29:37,371
There is no progression, there is no leveling up,

679
00:29:37,411 --> 00:29:39,292
there is no skills that you can choose.

680
00:29:39,392 --> 00:29:41,253
It's just the same character from start to finish.

681
00:29:42,466 --> 00:29:46,615
So how are we going to keep the player interested for 25 hours or more?

682
00:29:47,797 --> 00:29:51,444
And the first big thing we did is that we invented sort of, well we didn't invent them,

683
00:29:51,465 --> 00:29:54,170
we stole them from Commandos and so on, but, and we had these

684
00:29:54,673 --> 00:29:58,816
high impact features that completely change the gameplay,

685
00:29:58,836 --> 00:29:59,636
the core gameplay.

686
00:29:59,656 --> 00:30:00,897
And one of them is the night time,

687
00:30:01,017 --> 00:30:02,679
where the lights become very important,

688
00:30:02,699 --> 00:30:03,899
the shadows become important,

689
00:30:03,939 --> 00:30:06,361
which is something that is irrelevant on most maps,

690
00:30:07,262 --> 00:30:08,122
on day maps, I mean.

691
00:30:08,843 --> 00:30:10,364
And then you have the footprint mechanic,

692
00:30:10,384 --> 00:30:12,485
where snow is lying and guards can see your footprints

693
00:30:12,525 --> 00:30:13,286
and they will follow you up.

694
00:30:13,626 --> 00:30:16,048
And this really changes how you play a mission a lot.

695
00:30:16,328 --> 00:30:17,869
And we had these two things.

696
00:30:18,189 --> 00:30:19,010
We thought about others,

697
00:30:19,090 --> 00:30:21,191
like adding fog of war maybe to some missions,

698
00:30:21,332 --> 00:30:22,412
which sadly never made it.

699
00:30:22,432 --> 00:30:23,793
It's something I want to try, but.

700
00:30:24,425 --> 00:30:26,066
There's technical limitations with that.

701
00:30:26,106 --> 00:30:29,269
And it's difficult with the fog of war and a view cone,

702
00:30:29,289 --> 00:30:31,732
right, because the guard, you cannot see the guard,

703
00:30:31,752 --> 00:30:32,493
but he can see you.

704
00:30:32,533 --> 00:30:33,954
So that would have been very bad.

705
00:30:35,716 --> 00:30:38,158
So we did this thing, and we paste these out very carefully.

706
00:30:38,178 --> 00:30:39,259
I'm going to show you that in a minute.

707
00:30:39,279 --> 00:30:40,740
And we try to not overuse them.

708
00:30:42,362 --> 00:30:44,945
And then we have some sort of story high points in a mission.

709
00:30:45,005 --> 00:30:46,606
Usually, mechanically, the missions

710
00:30:46,646 --> 00:30:48,348
where we have these big assassinations,

711
00:30:48,408 --> 00:30:48,848
like you kill.

712
00:30:49,676 --> 00:30:53,918
Koto, you kill Iyabu or Kagesama in the end.

713
00:30:54,499 --> 00:30:56,580
There is not much going on from a mechanical standpoint.

714
00:30:56,600 --> 00:30:58,181
We don't introduce new features there.

715
00:30:58,221 --> 00:30:59,741
We don't introduce new characters.

716
00:31:00,082 --> 00:31:02,923
They're just, like you learn stuff,

717
00:31:03,043 --> 00:31:04,424
now use it and kill this guy.

718
00:31:04,544 --> 00:31:06,105
But you have an emotional high point there

719
00:31:06,145 --> 00:31:08,206
because story-wise it's pretty cool.

720
00:31:08,266 --> 00:31:09,827
So this is important for pacing as well.

721
00:31:10,627 --> 00:31:13,109
Especially balancing these two things against each other.

722
00:31:13,969 --> 00:31:14,970
We have these graphs that.

723
00:31:15,343 --> 00:31:20,526
I sadly didn't bring because I thought I would be a lot slower and didn't have time for it.

724
00:31:20,966 --> 00:31:25,769
So basically the idea was that we have these high impact features like this or introducing

725
00:31:25,809 --> 00:31:28,091
a character and we would assign a value to that, right?

726
00:31:28,531 --> 00:31:32,253
And then we would see in every mission how many high impact features are there, how many

727
00:31:32,333 --> 00:31:33,714
medium impact features are there.

728
00:31:33,734 --> 00:31:34,235
For example.

729
00:31:34,875 --> 00:31:37,016
puddles that you can go into that make a noise.

730
00:31:37,056 --> 00:31:38,537
They don't change the game completely,

731
00:31:38,597 --> 00:31:39,598
but they change it up a bit.

732
00:31:40,018 --> 00:31:41,078
And so we get this value,

733
00:31:42,019 --> 00:31:43,680
and then we can make a graph out of that

734
00:31:43,720 --> 00:31:45,961
and see how much is going on from a mechanic standpoint

735
00:31:45,981 --> 00:31:46,542
in every mission.

